  _eventName: 'Inflation: a year of economic pressure'
  _date: September 21, 2024
  _subheading: The year 2024 is characterized by a particularly tense economic context,
    marked by high inflation affecting household purchasing power and plunging part
    of the population into uncertainty. While inflation is often a cyclical phenomenon,
    this year's upsurge seems to have multiple causes, and its effects are being
    felt in many areas of daily life.
  _coverImage: {fileID: 21300000, guid: 63e7cdb0f96db1612b9b3ce7e5ed8081, type: 3}
  _captionImage: Aenean malesuada gravida diam, non tempus eros elementum vel. Phasellus
    pulvinar non nisl in sceler.
  _description: 'Inflation hitting all sectors: Inflation, which reached an average
    rate of 6.2% over the first six months of the year, is hitting consumers and
    businesses hard. At the top of the most significant increases, food and energy
    prices continue to rise at a sustained rate. Basic necessities, such as bread,
    milk, and fruit and vegetables, are seeing their cost rise exponentially, weighing
    heavily on household budgets. The energy sector is not spared, with a continuous
    rise in the prices of gas, electricity, and fuel, fueled by persistent geopolitical
    tensions and a still unstable global energy market. This increase has a direct
    impact on production costs, which ultimately generates a vicious circle of price
    increases. Added to this are housing costs, which are also experiencing an upward
    trend. Rents and real estate prices continue to rise in many major cities, exacerbating
    the difficulties of accessing decent housing for more and more French people.
    The consequences on the daily lives of the French: Faced with this inflation,
    households must adapt to cope with the increase in prices. For some, this translates
    into a revision of budgetary priorities: leisure and non-essential purchases
    are often put aside in favor of essential expenses. Low-income families, in particular,
    are those who suffer the most from this increase in prices, sometimes to the
    detriment of their quality of life. Economists agree that this inflation, although
    partly linked to the post-COVID recovery and the war in Ukraine, is also rooted
    in structural mechanisms. The global production chain remains fragile, transportation
    costs are high, and disruptions in supply chains have still not been completely
    resolved. Responses from public authorities: Faced with this situation, the government
    has implemented several measures to mitigate the impact of inflation on households.
    Direct aid, such as energy vouchers or the revaluation of social benefits, has
    been strengthened. In addition, ceilings have been introduced on certain basic
    necessities to prevent an uncontrollable surge in prices. However, these measures,
    although beneficial, are not always enough to compensate for the drop in purchasing
    power for a large part of the population. Trade unions and consumer associations
    are calling for more ambitious measures, including a general increase in wages
    to cope with the rise in prices. Short- and medium-term outlook: The biggest
    challenge for the coming months will be to stabilize the situation without plunging
    the economy into a recession. Experts expect a slight deceleration in inflation
    by the end of the year, but pressures remain strong, particularly in the energy
    and raw materials sectors. The monetary authorities, for their part, are continuing
    their efforts to control inflation by gradually raising interest rates, a policy
    that, although effective on paper, also has repercussions on access to credit
    and can slow down consumption. Conclusion: a situation that is weakening. While
    inflation is one of the cyclical economic phenomena, the current situation, marked
    by strong pressure on prices, is weakening many families and fueling a climate
    of economic uncertainty. While government responses have been put in place, it
    remains to be seen whether they will be sufficient to stem this inflationary
    spiral and restore purchasing power to the French. In the meantime, the population
    continues to navigate in an uncertain economic environment, where daily management
    is becoming a little more complicated every day. //Effect: increase in operating
    costs and costs for users'
